\section{Introduction} 

This narrative tells the story of a liaison between a deer spirit and a woman, and the troubles that came of it. The tale is one of many stories told by the Hupd’äh, who live in the Vaupés region, straddling the border of Brazil and Colombia (\figref{fig:hup:1}). Hup, the language of the Hupd’äh (lit. ‘person-\textsc{pl}’) belongs to the small Naduhup family (formerly known as Makú; see \citealt{EppsBolaños2017}); the speakers of the four Naduhup languages inhabit the interfluvial zones south of the Vaupés River and the middle Rio Negro. The approximately 2000 Hupd’äh live in communities ranging from a few families to several hundred people, located between the Vaupés and the Tiquié Rivers.
	
